00:05:51.730 --> 00:05:55.460
I want to start first by
just giving us a geographical

00:05:55.460 --> 00:05:58.950
reference as to where
we are in the world.

00:05:58.950 --> 00:06:03.640
Lake Hovsgol National Park is
the headwaters of the Selenge,

00:06:03.640 --> 00:06:05.380
one of the many headwaters
of the Selenge

00:06:05.380 --> 00:06:10.750
in north central Mongolia down
to Lake Baikal, and it flows

00:06:10.750 --> 00:06:12.860
into the Yenisei
River, which is one

00:06:12.860 --> 00:06:16.660
of the great Arctic
rivers in Siberia.

00:06:16.660 --> 00:06:21.090
Equally important, just to
the west is the Darkhad Valley

00:06:21.090 --> 00:06:24.330
and the Shishged River,
which also flows north

00:06:24.330 --> 00:06:28.400
into the Yenisei and
on to the Arctic.

00:06:28.400 --> 00:06:29.870
Lake Hovsgol National Park

00:06:29.870 --> 00:06:33.500
and the Lake Baikal region
is the southern extent

00:06:33.500 --> 00:06:36.870
of the permanent permafrost,
which is very important

00:06:36.870 --> 00:06:40.460
in the issues of climate
change as we move forward.

00:06:40.460 --> 00:06:43.240
And you can see from the
different colorations

00:06:43.240 --> 00:06:46.710
in this slide, the red arrow
pointing to Lake Hovsgol,

00:06:46.710 --> 00:06:49.720
that to the north is
the Siberian taiga,

00:06:49.720 --> 00:06:54.310
and to the south is the steppe,
the Central Asian steppe.

00:06:54.310 --> 00:06:57.300
So it's the blending
or the transition

00:06:57.300 --> 00:07:01.770
from one major ecosystem
to another.

00:07:01.770 --> 00:07:06.130
In local cultural
traditions, particularly

00:07:06.130 --> 00:07:08.620
in the Lake Hovsgol area,

00:07:08.620 --> 00:07:12.380
it is that Lake Hovsgol
itself is the Mother Sea.

00:07:12.380 --> 00:07:16.810
Munkh Saridag Mountain to the
north along the Russian border,

00:07:16.810 --> 00:07:20.340
looking over the frozen lake
and the Village of Hankh,

00:07:20.340 --> 00:07:26.410
is the Father and all life
emanated from the Father

00:07:26.410 --> 00:07:28.940
and the Great Mother Sea.

00:07:28.940 --> 00:07:32.570
So now the rangers of Lake
Hovsgol wanted to kind

00:07:32.570 --> 00:07:36.060
of take you on a quick
tour of the park.

00:07:36.060 --> 00:07:38.340
This is the entrance sign,
the new entrance sign,

00:07:38.340 --> 00:07:45.990
which was donated in 2015
by Yosemite National Park

00:07:45.990 --> 00:07:50.600
in the United States at the
time we signed a sister park

00:07:50.600 --> 00:07:54.150
agreement between Lake
Hovsgol and Yosemite.

00:07:54.150 --> 00:07:57.740
You can see here in the
geographic reference

00:07:57.740 --> 00:08:00.880
of the country, Lake Hovsgol
is that north central,

00:08:00.880 --> 00:08:05.510
and the colors just to the left
or the west, are the three parks

00:08:05.510 --> 00:08:08.000
that surround the
Darkhad Valley.

00:08:08.000 --> 00:08:12.410
The park itself is
1.2 million hectares.

00:08:12.410 --> 00:08:16.280
That's about Yellowstone
and a half again.

00:08:16.280 --> 00:08:18.880
Various transitions
of ecosystems.

00:08:18.880 --> 00:08:20.660
Seventy percent of
the fresh water

00:08:20.660 --> 00:08:22.900
in Mongolia sits in that lake.

00:08:22.900 --> 00:08:26.100
It's 267 meters deep.

00:08:26.100 --> 00:08:28.300
Sixty-eight mammal species
are known in the park

00:08:28.300 --> 00:08:30.520
and ten fish, one endemic.

00:08:30.520 --> 00:08:34.770
The Hovsgol Grayling only
lives in Lake Hovsgol.

00:08:34.770 --> 00:08:41.350
Local families and visitation,
which you will see shortly,

00:08:41.350 --> 00:08:46.810
is skyrocketing, and we'll
discuss the impacts of that.

00:08:46.810 --> 00:08:51.110
In 2013 the Mongol Ecology
Center worked with the park

00:08:51.110 --> 00:08:55.640
and developed a vision statement
for the management of the park,

00:08:55.640 --> 00:08:59.560
speaking to the diverse
cultural and natural resources

00:08:59.560 --> 00:09:01.340
that express the
values of the Mother Sea

00:09:01.340 --> 00:09:06.300
and the Father Mountain,
nomadic traditions and folklore,

00:09:06.300 --> 00:09:09.920
together for the
preservation, fully integrated

00:09:09.920 --> 00:09:13.270
with sustainable
economic development.

00:09:13.270 --> 00:09:15.410
This is the game changer.

00:09:15.410 --> 00:09:18.960
In the Soviet period
industrial export/import

00:09:18.960 --> 00:09:25.170
from the Soviet Union
for 1990 to 2010 or so,

00:09:25.170 --> 00:09:28.050
things were very quiet,
depressed economically

00:09:28.050 --> 00:09:33.490
in Hatgal, and then in 2014
the paved road from Ulaanbaatar

00:09:33.490 --> 00:09:37.030
to Hatgal was completed and
this is what has happened

00:09:37.030 --> 00:09:38.810
to the visitation.

00:09:38.810 --> 00:09:43.320
You can see early in the
2000s very little visitation.

00:09:43.320 --> 00:09:44.750
Once the road was completed,

00:09:44.750 --> 00:09:51.240
2017 almost 100,000
people visited the park,

00:09:51.240 --> 00:09:54.490
and a spike in international
tourism as well.

00:09:54.490 --> 00:09:58.230
The border between Russia and
Mongolia is now open to Russians

00:09:58.230 --> 00:10:00.980
and Mongolians, and
there's been a huge spike

00:10:00.980 --> 00:10:04.800
in the Russian traffic
from Irkutsk to other parts

00:10:04.800 --> 00:10:09.870
of the Lake Baikal region coming
down to visit Lake Hovsgol.

00:10:09.870 --> 00:10:14.680
The basis of any national
park in any country is law.

00:10:14.680 --> 00:10:18.100
Lake Hovsgol National Park
was established in 1992.

00:10:18.100 --> 00:10:23.050
Think about the timing there
in terms of the independence,

00:10:23.050 --> 00:10:27.020
the constitution, the
creation of the parliament

00:10:27.020 --> 00:10:29.080
and a very quick decision

00:10:29.080 --> 00:10:33.130
to preserve the area
around Lake Hovsgol.

00:10:33.130 --> 00:10:37.800
It wasn't until 1994, still
very quickly in the growth

00:10:37.800 --> 00:10:40.000
of a new nation, that the law

00:10:40.000 --> 00:10:43.110
on the protected
areas was established.

00:10:43.110 --> 00:10:45.940
For national parks it
set up special zones,

00:10:45.940 --> 00:10:49.700
sort of like our wilderness
areas, it set up travel

00:10:49.700 --> 00:10:53.830
and tourism zones, where
temporary structures

00:10:53.830 --> 00:10:56.380
and travel was restricted
but permissible,

00:10:56.380 --> 00:10:59.110
and the limited use
zones, where travel,

00:10:59.110 --> 00:11:04.970
permanent tourism facilities and
local families are authorized

00:11:04.970 --> 00:11:07.340
to live or allowed to live.

00:11:07.340 --> 00:11:11.920
So moving in to park
management issues, park zoning.

00:11:11.920 --> 00:11:14.790
This map was done in 2014.

00:11:14.790 --> 00:11:17.130
The pink area, it
is the special zone,

00:11:17.130 --> 00:11:18.820
the sort of wilderness zone.

00:11:18.820 --> 00:11:22.500
The tourism is the
blue, very limited areas

00:11:22.500 --> 00:11:23.960
that are called tourism,

00:11:23.960 --> 00:11:27.640
and then very large areas
for limited use zone.

00:11:27.640 --> 00:11:33.760
Limited use provides
no protection

00:11:33.760 --> 00:11:40.970
for fish spawning areas, small
natural areas, prime grasslands

00:11:40.970 --> 00:11:46.130
and the 574 local families
that live some or all

00:11:46.130 --> 00:11:49.740
of the year inside the park,
and you can see that number

00:11:49.740 --> 00:11:55.330
of livestock that they husband
within the park resources.

00:11:55.330 --> 00:11:57.250
In 1996 the parliament

00:11:57.250 --> 00:12:00.310
of Mongolia established
the international long-term

00:12:00.310 --> 00:12:03.790
ecological research site
to join a group of sites

00:12:03.790 --> 00:12:10.020
across the world important
in understanding the bio

00:12:10.020 --> 00:12:14.980
and general science
information about global issues,

00:12:14.980 --> 00:12:18.050
and this was established
in 1996.

00:12:18.050 --> 00:12:21.100
Research started then
and has been ongoing

00:12:21.100 --> 00:12:24.930
in this area ever since.

00:12:24.930 --> 00:12:28.840
Unfortunately, however,
in the Anjigas Valley,

00:12:28.840 --> 00:12:34.250
which you can see on the map,
in 2013 unlawful construction

00:12:34.250 --> 00:12:36.550
of a tourist facility.

00:12:36.550 --> 00:12:42.890
In 2014 limited use zone
extended 36 miles south

00:12:42.890 --> 00:12:45.550
from that line that
goes across the map.

00:12:45.550 --> 00:12:49.270
And then the permit for that
construction, 18 months later,

00:12:49.270 --> 00:12:54.150
was approved in December
of 2014.

00:12:54.150 --> 00:12:56.410
No laws were being followed,

00:12:56.410 --> 00:13:01.210
no standards were being
followed in that example.

00:13:01.210 --> 00:13:04.870
And that, unfortunately,
is not the only example.

00:13:04.870 --> 00:13:07.510
Mongolian standards
for tourism developed

00:13:07.510 --> 00:13:10.940
in protected areas
were developed in 2013,

00:13:10.940 --> 00:13:16.410
or a new set was established in
2013; 200 meters from the water,

00:13:16.410 --> 00:13:20.030
setback from the water, one
kilometer between facilities,

00:13:20.030 --> 00:13:22.330
no open toilets and livestock

00:13:22.330 --> 00:13:24.740
and tourism facilities
must be separated

00:13:24.740 --> 00:13:26.390
by a minimum of 500 meters.

00:13:26.390 --> 00:13:30.700
This is the classic example
of a local family trying

00:13:30.700 --> 00:13:34.270
to diversify economically,

00:13:34.270 --> 00:13:36.960
and it's a challenge
obviously relative

00:13:36.960 --> 00:13:41.130
to their standards
and what they can do.

00:13:41.130 --> 00:13:43.570
Here's a livestock
pen, an open toilet

00:13:43.570 --> 00:13:47.140
and a tourist facility
all within a stone's throw

00:13:47.140 --> 00:13:52.050
of each other, which
creates public health issues,

00:13:52.050 --> 00:13:54.350
as you can well imagine.

00:13:54.350 --> 00:13:57.010
In 2014 we did a
survey of the ger camps

00:13:57.010 --> 00:14:00.300
to identify the location
of all the camps

00:14:00.300 --> 00:14:02.880
on the southwest shore.

00:14:02.880 --> 00:14:05.670
2016 we came back
and did it again.

00:14:05.670 --> 00:14:09.760
The red are the new camps in
a two-year period of time.

00:14:09.760 --> 00:14:11.920
When you zoom down on this,

00:14:11.920 --> 00:14:13.910
you can see that the
average separation

00:14:13.910 --> 00:14:17.580
between camps is .27 meters.

00:14:17.580 --> 00:14:20.060
The standard is one kilometer.

00:14:20.060 --> 00:14:24.660
So again, the standard is not
being followed and the intensity

00:14:24.660 --> 00:14:28.020
of development is
critically impacting

00:14:28.020 --> 00:14:31.280
or has the long-term potential

00:14:31.280 --> 00:14:36.000
to critically impact the
quality of water in the lake.

00:14:36.000 --> 00:14:37.300
Visitor experience.

00:14:37.300 --> 00:14:41.900
I pulled this off the
Facebook page for Hatgal.

00:14:41.900 --> 00:14:47.150
A local Mongolian wrote
that the place was overrun,

00:14:47.150 --> 00:14:49.290
it was dusty, it was smoky.

00:14:49.290 --> 00:14:52.650
People can vacation, but do
they have to drink so much.

00:14:52.650 --> 00:14:55.770
They should drive slower, they
should take their trash out,

00:14:55.770 --> 00:14:57.830
stop driving on the grass.

00:14:57.830 --> 00:14:59.560
Local people.

00:14:59.560 --> 00:15:03.530
This is what they face
on a day-to-day basis.

00:15:03.530 --> 00:15:08.000
Litter, wild camping with
no toilets, wild camping,

00:15:08.000 --> 00:15:12.890
wild trash, no toilets,
right on the lake shore.

00:15:12.890 --> 00:15:17.810
Waste management also creates
plastic pollution, bottles,

00:15:17.810 --> 00:15:23.040
bags just dumped into various
depressions in the landscape

00:15:23.040 --> 00:15:27.620
and over time, from sun and
wind, they degenerate and end

00:15:27.620 --> 00:15:31.960
up in the lake, creating hazards
for the fish, creating hazards

00:15:31.960 --> 00:15:35.670
in any water that's consumed
through the bioaccumulation

00:15:35.670 --> 00:15:38.200
of plastic in the systems.

00:15:38.200 --> 00:15:42.260
The Mongol Ecology Center Junior
Ranger Program did water quality

00:15:42.260 --> 00:15:46.250
sampling this last
summer, five test sites.

00:15:46.250 --> 00:15:49.860
Five sites found the water to
be clear, found the water to be

00:15:49.860 --> 00:15:55.970
at the appropriate pH, found the
water to be low in nutrients,

00:15:55.970 --> 00:15:59.960
but found the water to
contain fecal coliform.

00:15:59.960 --> 00:16:04.280
The issue is just at the
edge of being serious,

00:16:04.280 --> 00:16:08.720
but it's certainly an alarm
bell that needs to be watched.

00:16:08.720 --> 00:16:13.000
Oil and gas pollution from
water craft, old boats,

00:16:13.000 --> 00:16:18.230
two-cycle engines and public
safety is a serious concern

00:16:18.230 --> 00:16:23.400
as far as dealing with folks
using boats on the water.

00:16:23.400 --> 00:16:26.460
There are more than
70 private operators,

00:16:26.460 --> 00:16:28.860
unregulated private operators

00:16:28.860 --> 00:16:32.430
with tour boat type
activities on Lake Hovsgol.

00:16:32.430 --> 00:16:36.060
Park roads, the road
on the left is the road

00:16:36.060 --> 00:16:38.020
from Hatgal to Hankh.

00:16:38.020 --> 00:16:41.160
The road on the right
is an improved road

00:16:41.160 --> 00:16:44.480
on the southwest
shore of the lake.

