00:22:18.320 --> 00:22:22.790
And the role that I'm trying to
play here is to give you a bit

00:22:22.790 --> 00:22:28.830
of the science, our scientific
understanding of Lake Hovsgol

00:22:28.830 --> 00:22:32.980
and why it is so sensitive
to the kinds of problems

00:22:32.980 --> 00:22:35.450
that Bob has just discussed.

00:22:35.450 --> 00:22:39.930
It is a tectonic basin,
similar to Baikal.

00:22:39.930 --> 00:22:43.910
Baikal, of course, is
about 22 million years old.

00:22:43.910 --> 00:22:47.090
Hovsgol itself is only
about 5 million years old

00:22:47.090 --> 00:22:50.490
and was formed during one
of the last tectonic phases

00:22:50.490 --> 00:22:56.290
that extended the size of Lake
Baikal, but added Lake Hovsgol,

00:22:56.290 --> 00:22:59.080
but it's separate, of course,
though they are connected

00:22:59.080 --> 00:23:02.390
by the Selenge River,
as Bob said.

00:23:02.390 --> 00:23:05.060
The lake is reasonably large.

00:23:05.060 --> 00:23:09.420
Its surface area is about
the size of Lake Erie.

00:23:09.420 --> 00:23:13.210
Though Lake Erie is around
55 meters deep, Lake Hovsgol

00:23:13.210 --> 00:23:16.170
and these tectonic
basins are much deeper.

00:23:16.170 --> 00:23:23.150
This is 262 meters deep, and
because of that large volume

00:23:23.150 --> 00:23:28.780
of water, it's the 16th
largest lake in the world.

00:23:28.780 --> 00:23:33.080
Baikal, of course,
is the largest lake.

00:23:33.080 --> 00:23:36.890
The watershed has
been a summer home

00:23:36.890 --> 00:23:40.600
for nomadic herders
for centuries.

00:23:40.600 --> 00:23:45.220
I mean, you probably can go
back at least 2,000 years,

00:23:45.220 --> 00:23:52.270
if not longer in time, where
herders have been coming

00:23:52.270 --> 00:23:55.810
into the valley there,
or to valleys, actually.

00:23:55.810 --> 00:23:59.360
And, of course, one of
the most important things,

00:23:59.360 --> 00:24:02.000
and most of you familiar
with Mongolia know

00:24:02.000 --> 00:24:04.680
that often they have
very serious droughts.

00:24:04.680 --> 00:24:07.880
So where do you go to get
water during a drought;

00:24:07.880 --> 00:24:09.500
you try to go to a river.

00:24:09.500 --> 00:24:12.230
You look at the rivers and
they're totally overgrazed,

00:24:12.230 --> 00:24:17.620
in terms of the watershed of
the river during a drought.

00:24:17.620 --> 00:24:20.090
Hovsgol itself can
become overgrazed, too,

00:24:20.090 --> 00:24:26.320
but it becomes a really
important place for the herders

00:24:26.320 --> 00:24:30.250
to be able to take their
animals to get water

00:24:30.250 --> 00:24:34.730
and generally get good pasture.

00:24:34.730 --> 00:24:39.170
The herders are coming,
in this case,

00:24:39.170 --> 00:24:43.660
from their winter grazing area,
which is up in the mountains,

00:24:43.660 --> 00:24:47.510
and they come down into the
valleys during the summer,

00:24:47.510 --> 00:24:50.700
and then again in the autumn
will start heading back

00:24:50.700 --> 00:24:53.470
up to the top of the
mountains, and that is simply

00:24:53.470 --> 00:24:58.100
because the valleys during the
winter are very, very cold.

00:24:58.100 --> 00:25:03.160
So actually, you can feel
it as you walk up yourself.

00:25:03.160 --> 00:25:06.070
You're four to five
degrees warmer as you go

00:25:06.070 --> 00:25:08.910
up towards the top
of the mountain.

00:25:08.910 --> 00:25:12.060
And you can see also in
that picture, by the way,

00:25:12.060 --> 00:25:18.060
they're carrying their ger,
all of their possessions,

00:25:18.060 --> 00:25:21.460
on the back of yaks here,
and then you can see

00:25:21.460 --> 00:25:27.050
in the background up above the
sheep, goats, cashmere goats

00:25:27.050 --> 00:25:30.210
and other animals
coming down the valley.

00:25:30.210 --> 00:25:32.160
Most herders will
have at least four,

00:25:32.160 --> 00:25:35.390
possibly five different
species of animals

00:25:35.390 --> 00:25:38.420
that they have in their herds.

00:25:38.420 --> 00:25:44.120
And in general, what you'll
see is that the goats,

00:25:44.120 --> 00:25:48.070
the cashmere goats and the
sheep, are grazing up on slopes.

00:25:48.070 --> 00:25:51.490
Horses and yaks are down
below, down near the river.

00:25:51.490 --> 00:25:54.900
So they're actually
separated ecologically.

00:25:54.900 --> 00:26:00.180
So even though you have a
number of fairly large herds,

00:26:00.180 --> 00:26:03.400
they really are sort
of exploiting as much

00:26:03.400 --> 00:26:05.970
of the slope environment
as they can.

00:26:10.040 --> 00:26:15.700
The problems that Bob
has alluded to in terms

00:26:15.700 --> 00:26:19.220
of construction are
really mirrored, of course,

00:26:19.220 --> 00:26:24.340
in the ecology, the ecological
changes that are occurring now.

00:26:24.340 --> 00:26:28.640
And what we're seeing
now is that more and more

00:26:28.640 --> 00:26:32.370
of the watersheds, as
they're being developed

00:26:32.370 --> 00:26:37.180
for these ger camps and
the shoreline of the lake,

00:26:37.180 --> 00:26:42.140
that those areas of the
lake that are closest

00:26:42.140 --> 00:26:46.860
to the shore are starting to
very serious blooms of algae.

00:26:46.860 --> 00:26:50.950
This is the kind of problem
that most people don't think

00:26:50.950 --> 00:26:55.970
of as a serious problem at
first, but as it expands

00:26:55.970 --> 00:26:59.060
and those areas become
more and more polluted,

00:26:59.060 --> 00:27:03.300
which is really what this is
all about, people become less

00:27:03.300 --> 00:27:05.630
and less interested
in going there.

00:27:05.630 --> 00:27:08.760
You don't want to have to
go to a lake and get out

00:27:08.760 --> 00:27:12.070
and take a shower afterwards
so you can clean all the scum,

00:27:12.070 --> 00:27:15.620
the algae scum off of you,
and yet that's starting

00:27:15.620 --> 00:27:18.590
to occur more and more.

00:27:18.590 --> 00:27:21.920
Another aspect of that, in
terms of that's a problem

00:27:21.920 --> 00:27:24.830
of nutrient loading,
a lot of it from trash

00:27:24.830 --> 00:27:29.260
and any erosion coming
off of the landscape,

00:27:29.260 --> 00:27:31.930
and I'll explain what that
problem is in a minute,

00:27:31.930 --> 00:27:35.800
but the other part is that
with rapid warming due

00:27:35.800 --> 00:27:39.230
to climate change, the whole
area has already warmed,

00:27:39.230 --> 00:27:42.950
is warming two to three times
faster than we are warming

00:27:42.950 --> 00:27:46.130
with climate change,
and we talk mostly here

00:27:46.130 --> 00:27:50.910
about a one degree warming
over the last 40 or 50 years.

00:27:50.910 --> 00:27:55.470
In Mongolia and in parts -- much
of Siberia you're really talking

00:27:55.470 --> 00:27:58.650
about at least a
three degree warming,

00:28:00.300 --> 00:28:02.290
and a lot of that is simply

00:28:02.290 --> 00:28:06.090
because the snow is melting
very rapidly, so that rather

00:28:06.090 --> 00:28:11.590
than sunlight being
reflected back by the snow,

00:28:11.590 --> 00:28:14.680
so the heatiness [phonetic]
is sort of reflected back.

00:28:14.680 --> 00:28:16.790
In fact, now, that
heat that's coming

00:28:16.790 --> 00:28:20.000
from the sun is being
absorbed by the landscape

00:28:20.000 --> 00:28:24.320
and that's why the warming is
occurring much more rapidly.

00:28:24.320 --> 00:28:25.750
And then finally,
as I mentioned,

00:28:25.750 --> 00:28:29.810
the increased trash
accumulation.

00:28:29.810 --> 00:28:34.880
So I'm going to focus on those
three points here very quickly.

00:28:34.880 --> 00:28:37.670
Mongolia is generally
known, to begin with,

00:28:37.670 --> 00:28:39.570
as the Blue Pearl of Mongolia.

00:28:39.570 --> 00:28:41.010
Have any of you heard
of that before?

00:28:41.010 --> 00:28:42.310
[ Inaudible responses ]

00:28:42.310 --> 00:28:46.000
I just wondered, because
I started there in 1994

00:28:46.000 --> 00:28:51.000
and that was the
first thing I learned.

00:28:51.000 --> 00:28:53.620
Mongolians love pearls,
to begin with.

00:28:53.620 --> 00:28:56.840
I'm pretty sure I'm
saying that correctly.

00:28:56.840 --> 00:28:59.720
And so when they say the
Blue Pearl, you can see why.

00:28:59.720 --> 00:29:02.060
It's really a gorgeous color.

00:29:02.060 --> 00:29:05.200
The water is so clear, and
what happens is that with --

00:29:05.200 --> 00:29:10.810
as you know, a rainbow has all
of the speck tore of colors,

00:29:10.810 --> 00:29:14.020
colored light in it, but
as light goes down through,

00:29:14.020 --> 00:29:17.390
that sunlight goes
down through the water,

00:29:17.390 --> 00:29:21.450
different wavelengths, different
colors are being absorbed

00:29:21.450 --> 00:29:22.960
and removed.

00:29:22.960 --> 00:29:25.860
And the one wavelength of light

00:29:25.860 --> 00:29:30.030
that goes the deepest
is blue light and then

00:29:30.030 --> 00:29:34.730
that is reflected back
to the sky and the lakes,

00:29:34.730 --> 00:29:39.590
in other words, as the ocean,
is so clear that the light

00:29:39.590 --> 00:29:41.860
that comes back to
you when you look

00:29:41.860 --> 00:29:44.970
down on the lake
is that blue light.

00:29:44.970 --> 00:29:47.880
Everything else has
been filtered out.

00:29:48.910 --> 00:29:51.510
The reason I mention
this, of course,

00:29:51.510 --> 00:29:55.290
is this is what we want it to
look like, this is what you want

00:29:55.290 --> 00:29:56.980
to see when you get there,

00:29:56.980 --> 00:29:59.070
but the question is
are you always going

00:29:59.070 --> 00:30:04.990
to be able to see it.

00:30:04.990 --> 00:30:09.880
The concept of pollution that
we refer to in water and lakes

00:30:09.880 --> 00:30:14.580
in particular, such as the Great
Lakes, we don't really talk

00:30:14.580 --> 00:30:16.800
about pollution, but we could,

00:30:16.800 --> 00:30:20.090
but there is a term
eutrophication that I think many

00:30:20.090 --> 00:30:25.700
of you perhaps have
heard of before.

00:30:25.700 --> 00:30:32.360
Eutrophication is a phenomenon
where a water body is shifting

00:30:32.360 --> 00:30:37.910
from a low productive,
low nutrient system,

00:30:37.910 --> 00:30:46.150
with very clear, clean water,
to a more polluted water,

00:30:46.150 --> 00:30:49.770
where nutrients are coming
in stimulating algae growth.

00:30:49.770 --> 00:30:54.850
That algae growth, in turn,
builds up a large plant biomass

00:30:54.850 --> 00:30:57.860
in the water so it
clouds the water,

00:30:57.860 --> 00:31:02.380
and then when that bloom dies
out, it falls to the bottom

00:31:02.380 --> 00:31:06.010
into the sediments
of the lake and then

00:31:06.010 --> 00:31:08.080
that begins to decompose.

00:31:08.080 --> 00:31:10.790
Especially in a lake like
Hovsgol, where you have a lot

00:31:10.790 --> 00:31:14.000
of oxygen already present
in that bottom water,

00:31:14.000 --> 00:31:19.040
that plant material, dead
plant material is decomposing,

00:31:19.040 --> 00:31:22.690
decomposing and decomposing
and taking up oxygen,

00:31:22.690 --> 00:31:25.180
drinking oxygen continuously.

00:31:25.180 --> 00:31:28.710
And so it's grabbing the
oxygen out of the water

00:31:28.710 --> 00:31:30.640
and slowly these kinds of lakes

00:31:30.640 --> 00:31:33.450
that are undergoing
eutrophication,

00:31:33.450 --> 00:31:36.470
becoming more productive,
what happens is

00:31:36.470 --> 00:31:41.710
that the mud itself
loses its oxygen.

00:31:41.710 --> 00:31:44.380
The water above it loses oxygen.

00:31:44.380 --> 00:31:47.390
And when that happens,
the nutrients

00:31:47.390 --> 00:31:50.010
that have been suspended
in the water column,

00:31:50.010 --> 00:31:55.740
and particularly a nutrient
like phosphorus, that has gone

00:31:55.740 --> 00:31:59.560
down to the bottom,
remained in the sediment

00:31:59.560 --> 00:32:04.680
under these high oxygen
conditions, when it loses

00:32:04.680 --> 00:32:08.790
that oxygen, that phosphorus
especially, some nitrogen,

00:32:08.790 --> 00:32:12.360
but particularly
phosphorous, now can emerge

00:32:12.360 --> 00:32:16.200
from the sediments and it
comes back up into the water

00:32:16.200 --> 00:32:18.950
and fertilizes the
growth of algae.

00:32:18.950 --> 00:32:23.070
So that what basically
is happening is

00:32:23.070 --> 00:32:27.480
that as you're undergoing
this gradual increase

00:32:27.480 --> 00:32:31.720
in productivity, increase
of growth of plant material

00:32:31.720 --> 00:32:37.570
in the water column, it is
then regenerating itself,

00:32:37.570 --> 00:32:40.020
recovering those
nutrients, bringing it back

00:32:40.020 --> 00:32:44.480
up into the water and so
you not only have the influx

00:32:44.480 --> 00:32:48.590
of nutrients from the watershed,
but you now have an influx,

00:32:48.590 --> 00:32:51.040
as it were, from the sediment.

00:32:51.040 --> 00:32:56.150
So it's a reinforcement effect
that builds up very quickly,

00:32:56.150 --> 00:32:57.700
and this really increases.

00:32:57.700 --> 00:33:05.050
The lakes that you've seen
maybe here in Virginia or in --

00:33:05.050 --> 00:33:07.820
no, we're not in
Virginia, sorry --

00:33:07.820 --> 00:33:11.700
in Pennsylvania where
I come from, in Kansas,

00:33:11.700 --> 00:33:15.540
in Indiana where I've
studied lakes before,

00:33:15.540 --> 00:33:19.000
you start to get ponds,
especially Michigan,

00:33:19.000 --> 00:33:21.120
or Lake Erie, many
of you know --

00:33:21.120 --> 00:33:24.280
remember the description
of Lake Erie?

00:33:24.280 --> 00:33:26.910
Lake Erie is dead.

00:33:26.910 --> 00:33:28.350
What did they mean by that?

00:33:28.350 --> 00:33:31.850
What they actually meant,
obviously the water was there,

00:33:31.850 --> 00:33:34.430
the basin was there,
it's all there,

00:33:34.430 --> 00:33:39.630
but you don't find very much
life in many areas of the lake,

00:33:39.630 --> 00:33:44.110
and it's that living material,
of course, that has died,

00:33:44.110 --> 00:33:46.120
has released its nutrients.

00:33:46.120 --> 00:33:51.300
They've gone back up in that
reinforcing kind of change

00:33:51.300 --> 00:33:58.250
that is going on, but it chokes
out the oxygen so that many

00:33:58.250 --> 00:34:03.590
of the organisms present,
fishes, et cetera, are dying.

00:34:03.590 --> 00:34:08.290
It's a very serious problem, and
that's why Lake Erie was said

00:34:08.290 --> 00:34:11.400
to be dead, though it's not,
and hopefully it's starting

00:34:11.400 --> 00:34:15.890
to return, in fact, but
it's reversing itself again.

00:34:17.110 --> 00:34:22.500
So what are the kinds of
problems that are causing this.

00:34:22.500 --> 00:34:26.420
Water quality studies of the
tributary streams that we did

00:34:26.420 --> 00:34:31.860
in 1999 to 2000 found that
livestock grazing itself,

00:34:31.860 --> 00:34:34.950
this is before tourism
really built up,

00:34:34.950 --> 00:34:38.490
livestock grazing itself
is fertilizing algae

00:34:38.490 --> 00:34:42.340
and plant growth, as just
described, mostly in the bays

00:34:42.340 --> 00:34:44.010
or in the near shore areas.

00:34:44.010 --> 00:34:46.760
Those are the areas that
are being hit first.

00:34:46.760 --> 00:34:49.500
And, of course, those are
the areas that tourists want

00:34:49.500 --> 00:34:52.090
to spend their time in.

00:34:52.090 --> 00:34:54.880
The increased photosynthesis
then increases --

00:34:54.880 --> 00:34:58.290
and this is an interesting
point, but it can end

00:34:58.290 --> 00:35:05.140
up increasing the alkalinity
of the water and when

00:35:05.140 --> 00:35:08.780
that alkalinity -- in one
bay that we measured --

00:35:08.780 --> 00:35:14.060
if you know the pH scale,
neutral is around seven

00:35:14.060 --> 00:35:16.420
and you go up to
ten, you're really

00:35:16.420 --> 00:35:20.490
in a very alkaline situation,
or you go down to four or five,

00:35:20.490 --> 00:35:22.390
you're in a very acid system.

00:35:22.390 --> 00:35:29.130
We found one area, one bay with
fish kills with a pH of 9.8.

00:35:29.130 --> 00:35:33.710
I won't go into the reason
for that, but if anyone wants

00:35:33.710 --> 00:35:35.310
to know, we can discuss it.

00:35:35.310 --> 00:35:41.370
One of the really key points to
understand about Lake Hovsgol is

00:35:41.370 --> 00:35:47.140
that most of the geology in
that area consists of dolomite,

00:35:47.140 --> 00:35:50.580
sort of a limestone, a
slight variation on the theme

00:35:50.580 --> 00:35:58.590
of limestone, but this dolomite
is very rich in phosphorus.

00:35:58.590 --> 00:36:02.770
And again, phosphorus
is a major nutrient,

00:36:02.770 --> 00:36:08.380
if not the major nutrient
limiting this plant growth

00:36:08.380 --> 00:36:09.700
in lakes.

00:36:09.700 --> 00:36:16.710
So the whole effect of
the watershed coming in,

00:36:16.710 --> 00:36:19.560
the nutrients from the
watershed coming in,

00:36:19.560 --> 00:36:22.930
going into the sediment,
being regenerated back

00:36:22.930 --> 00:36:29.000
up into the water, is being
reinforced overall by half

00:36:29.000 --> 00:36:34.040
of the watershed of Lake
Hovsgol, consisting of dolomite

00:36:34.040 --> 00:36:37.710
that is loaded with phosphorus.

00:36:37.710 --> 00:36:40.390
Anything that is done
in the lake almost

00:36:40.390 --> 00:36:45.800
without care is going to end up
being a problem in Lake Hovsgol.

00:36:45.800 --> 00:36:50.990
The issue on this, of
course, I said unregulated

00:36:50.990 --> 00:36:56.910
as a point there, the
lake is very sensitive.

00:36:56.910 --> 00:37:04.150
If it is regulated with
the kinds of things

00:37:04.150 --> 00:37:08.210
that Bob was talking
about, you don't have to end

00:37:08.210 --> 00:37:10.400
up with this kind of a problem.

00:37:10.400 --> 00:37:14.330
If those ger camps keep
being built the way

00:37:14.330 --> 00:37:16.820
that they were described,

00:37:16.820 --> 00:37:19.060
you can imagine what's
going to happen.

00:37:19.060 --> 00:37:21.730
It's going to be very
serious in the future.

00:37:21.730 --> 00:37:26.240
Right now I happen to be
involved with a project

00:37:26.240 --> 00:37:28.730
from the Asian Development Bank,

00:37:28.730 --> 00:37:33.850
where the bank is very
appropriately investing a great

00:37:33.850 --> 00:37:37.180
deal of money trying
to help the people

00:37:37.180 --> 00:37:40.520
of Lake Hovsgol develop
a tourism industry

00:37:40.520 --> 00:37:44.800
and the issue is, of course,

00:37:44.800 --> 00:37:47.480
which direction is
it going to take.

00:37:47.480 --> 00:37:51.380
Is it going to take a
regulated direction,

00:37:51.380 --> 00:37:56.580
where everyone follows the best
guidelines to protect the lake,

00:37:56.580 --> 00:37:59.060
or is it going to
go in a direction

00:37:59.060 --> 00:38:01.440
where people ignore
those problems,

00:38:01.440 --> 00:38:07.670
as they are doing right now,
and causing the lake to go

00:38:07.670 --> 00:38:10.970
in a direction of
very serious problems.

00:38:14.200 --> 00:38:17.900
As some of you know, Baikal is
becoming more and more polluted

00:38:17.900 --> 00:38:21.630
in many areas and what you
see in the watershed now,

00:38:21.630 --> 00:38:25.020
more and more, are these
kinds of algae growths,

00:38:25.020 --> 00:38:28.020
and that's the kind of
thing, most certainly,

00:38:28.020 --> 00:38:31.170
not only on the bottom --
these are benthic algae growing

00:38:31.170 --> 00:38:33.220
on the bottom, but
also up in the water,

00:38:33.220 --> 00:38:35.520
so the water turns green.

00:38:39.040 --> 00:38:42.520
Then you have the whole
aspect of climate change.

00:38:42.520 --> 00:38:45.740
So we have this problem
with nutrients in the lake.

00:38:45.740 --> 00:38:49.200
We also have a problem with
climate change, and I think many

00:38:49.200 --> 00:38:50.900
of you have been
introduced to that enough

00:38:50.900 --> 00:38:55.410
so that you'll appreciate
what I'm referring to here.

00:38:55.410 --> 00:38:59.940
We've been doing interviews
with nomadic herders and trying

00:38:59.940 --> 00:39:04.470
to get their perceptions,
understand their perceptions

00:39:04.470 --> 00:39:07.970
of how climate change is
affecting their lives.

00:39:11.040 --> 00:39:14.320
And these are some of the
questions and the responses,

00:39:14.320 --> 00:39:17.110
just to give you an idea
of how the herders --

00:39:17.110 --> 00:39:19.190
and let me say one thing.

00:39:19.190 --> 00:39:23.840
Some people, when you're a
[inaudible], seem to suggest,

00:39:23.840 --> 00:39:26.170
oh, those herders, they don't
know what they're doing,

00:39:26.170 --> 00:39:29.230
you know, they're just going
around out there somewhere,

00:39:29.230 --> 00:39:32.340
not really protecting
their environment.

00:39:32.340 --> 00:39:36.070
In fact, in my mind
it's quite the opposite.

00:39:36.070 --> 00:39:37.460
They're very concerned

00:39:37.460 --> 00:39:40.090
and they're extremely
good observers.

00:39:40.090 --> 00:39:42.660
So what is the biggest
environmental impact

00:39:42.660 --> 00:39:47.540
on the lives of the herders,
as they responded to us.

00:39:47.540 --> 00:39:50.980
The first issue is
changing weather.

00:39:50.980 --> 00:39:53.520
It's not saying weather,

00:39:53.520 --> 00:39:56.180
which we all complain
about the weather.

00:39:56.180 --> 00:39:58.540
They're complaining about
the weather changing.

00:39:58.540 --> 00:40:04.290
Actually, over the last few days
maybe we've had a lot change,

00:40:04.290 --> 00:40:05.590
but.

00:40:05.590 --> 00:40:09.950
Overgrazing is much less a
serious problem for herders

00:40:09.950 --> 00:40:12.760
as is the changing weather.

00:40:12.760 --> 00:40:15.110
And then you ask them
are the seasons changing,

00:40:15.110 --> 00:40:18.420
trying to break down that
whole idea and other aspects

00:40:18.420 --> 00:40:21.800
of what they mean
by changing weather.

00:40:21.800 --> 00:40:24.120
The timing of the
seasons has changed,

00:40:24.120 --> 00:40:25.420
and this is really important.

00:40:25.420 --> 00:40:29.070
As you know, nomadic
herders that are moving

00:40:29.070 --> 00:40:32.670
to the mountaintops during
the winter, they start moving

00:40:32.670 --> 00:40:36.090
in autumn, they have to
know when to start moving,

00:40:36.090 --> 00:40:38.820
and traditionally they have
usually started sometime

00:40:38.820 --> 00:40:41.170
in late August, early September.

00:40:41.170 --> 00:40:44.110
Remember, that's
pretty far north.

00:40:44.110 --> 00:40:49.320
So they have a timing for when
they move up into the mountains

00:40:49.320 --> 00:40:53.030
to get away from the cold
valleys, and they have a timing

00:40:53.030 --> 00:40:58.170
for when they move back down
to the valleys in the spring

00:40:58.170 --> 00:41:02.660
because they have to always
worry about their water sources.

00:41:02.660 --> 00:41:06.580
So the timing of the
seasons has changed

00:41:06.580 --> 00:41:10.970
and it is creating substantial
problems for the herders.

00:41:10.970 --> 00:41:13.900
The winters are milder,
as you would expect.

00:41:13.900 --> 00:41:18.440
Summers are cooler, but are
mixed with very warm days and,

00:41:18.440 --> 00:41:23.280
in fact, they now say that
they are having heatwaves,

00:41:23.280 --> 00:41:26.160
in the same way that
we have heatwaves,

00:41:26.160 --> 00:41:31.390
and that the heatwaves
are burning the grass.

00:41:31.390 --> 00:41:35.550
And finally, and the thing
that I want to emphasize here

00:41:35.550 --> 00:41:38.390
for the next couple of slides,

00:41:38.390 --> 00:41:43.030
is they say the rains have
changed, and they will describe

00:41:43.030 --> 00:41:49.350
to you that rains used to be a
light silky rain that might last

00:41:49.350 --> 00:41:52.290
for two or three days.

00:41:52.290 --> 00:41:55.340
Now, it's coming in gushes.

00:41:55.340 --> 00:41:58.270
And you've seen that, I'm
sure, yourself around here,

00:41:58.270 --> 00:42:00.140
so I'm not telling you anything

00:42:00.140 --> 00:42:03.100
that you haven't
witnessed as a change.

00:42:03.100 --> 00:42:07.840
And I think if you
consider all the things

00:42:07.840 --> 00:42:10.680
that have been occurring with
some of these really heavy rains

00:42:10.680 --> 00:42:13.970
where it washes cars off
of Long Island Expressway,

00:42:13.970 --> 00:42:16.890
and there was one big storm
that came out of Chicago

00:42:16.890 --> 00:42:20.280
and came right down to
Washington area here,

00:42:20.280 --> 00:42:26.480
flooded tremendously, these are
not historically common events.

00:42:26.480 --> 00:42:29.940
They may have occasionally
occurred in the past,

00:42:29.940 --> 00:42:33.250
but they are increasing
in frequency.

00:42:33.250 --> 00:42:36.730
For Mongolia, what
you're beginning

00:42:36.730 --> 00:42:40.740
to see now are these
really heavy,

00:42:40.740 --> 00:42:44.020
hard rains that are coming
in and they look like this,

00:42:44.020 --> 00:42:48.330
if you can sort of -- I hope
you can see, right in the center

00:42:48.330 --> 00:42:53.120
above those houses, there's a
very heavy rainstorm occurring.

00:42:53.120 --> 00:42:55.650
That happens to be south
of us and we just happened

00:42:55.650 --> 00:42:57.650
to be heading that way.

00:42:57.650 --> 00:43:00.760
This kind of a rain
is called a --

00:43:00.760 --> 00:43:04.550
by the Mongols is
called an aadar rain.

00:43:04.550 --> 00:43:08.620
Many of you fluent in
Mongolia will know that term.

00:43:08.620 --> 00:43:14.560
This is the kind of rain you
don't want to stand outside

00:43:14.560 --> 00:43:19.180
and feel this warm rain
coming down on you.

00:43:19.180 --> 00:43:20.480
That would have been the kind

00:43:20.480 --> 00:43:23.590
of rain they would
expect in the past.

00:43:23.590 --> 00:43:28.030
Now what they're finding
are cold rains coming down,

00:43:28.030 --> 00:43:34.490
large drops that are coming down
very rapidly on top of them,

00:43:34.490 --> 00:43:38.500
and they become very, very
concerned about their children

00:43:38.500 --> 00:43:40.340
when there are children
are outside.

00:43:40.340 --> 00:43:43.910
Some of these rains are so hard
that they can kill animals,

00:43:43.910 --> 00:43:46.650
and I'm not exaggerating that.

00:43:46.650 --> 00:43:49.260
I hope you appreciate.

00:43:49.260 --> 00:43:52.010
Just to show you now,
this happens to be --

00:43:52.010 --> 00:43:55.430
one of the things that the
herders say was, again,

00:43:55.430 --> 00:43:59.210
we used to have these two- or
three-day rains, half day maybe,

00:43:59.210 --> 00:44:02.840
a couple of days, light rains.

00:44:02.840 --> 00:44:06.100
Now we're having
really intense rains.

00:44:06.100 --> 00:44:08.730
Overall there's not a big
increase in the amount

00:44:08.730 --> 00:44:13.720
of rainfall annually, it's
just coming delivered now,

00:44:13.720 --> 00:44:17.900
instead of a slow, gradual rain,
it's coming down in torrents.

00:44:17.900 --> 00:44:20.440
It's coming down
very hard, as I said.

00:44:20.440 --> 00:44:23.400
And what you see on this
graph is that everything

00:44:23.400 --> 00:44:26.480
above that horizontal line,

00:44:26.480 --> 00:44:29.430
where on the top there
it says aadar rain,

00:44:29.430 --> 00:44:33.810
every rain above that
line is an aadar rain,

00:44:33.810 --> 00:44:38.240
and this is a very,
very heavy rain.

00:44:38.240 --> 00:44:44.980
This is from 2008,
2009, 2010, 2011, 2012.

00:44:44.980 --> 00:44:46.280
Every year.

00:44:46.280 --> 00:44:49.790
The number on top of the
line represents the length

00:44:49.790 --> 00:44:51.540
of that rain.

00:44:51.540 --> 00:44:55.000
So, for example, look at 2010.

00:44:55.000 --> 00:44:59.410
You have rains that are
aadar rains, very hard rains

00:44:59.410 --> 00:45:07.180
that are lasting 15, 30,
15 minutes, ten minutes,

00:45:07.180 --> 00:45:11.270
five minutes, with three
millimeters every five

00:45:11.270 --> 00:45:13.710
minutes occurring.

00:45:13.710 --> 00:45:15.870
Now, that may not
sound like very much,

00:45:15.870 --> 00:45:18.970
but that's a lot of
rain coming down.

00:45:23.050 --> 00:45:26.880
And this is what the herders say
as a result of our interviews

00:45:26.880 --> 00:45:28.540
and discussing it with them.

00:45:28.540 --> 00:45:31.360
The herders claim the aadar
rains were very damaging

00:45:31.360 --> 00:45:34.240
to their pastures, animals

00:45:34.240 --> 00:45:36.750
and to their families
while watching the herds.

00:45:36.750 --> 00:45:39.190
They're very concerned
about their children,

00:45:39.190 --> 00:45:43.110
especially when they're out
because often the child will go

00:45:43.110 --> 00:45:47.290
out without a shirt on and then
you have one of these cold,

00:45:47.290 --> 00:45:50.260
drenching rains come
down and, of course,

00:45:50.260 --> 00:45:53.490
hypothermia then becomes
a very serious problem.

00:45:53.490 --> 00:45:55.720
It's very common now.

00:45:55.720 --> 00:46:01.640
The rain eroded the road,
very intense, dangerous.

00:46:01.640 --> 00:46:04.370
The ger was flooded,
mattresses were floating,

00:46:04.370 --> 00:46:06.980
pasture covered with
running water.

00:46:06.980 --> 00:46:11.220
That's not typical,
certainly not historically.

00:46:11.220 --> 00:46:13.280
In previous year -- these
are different herders

00:46:13.280 --> 00:46:14.960
that are telling us this.

00:46:14.960 --> 00:46:18.670
In previous year, 2011,
had extremely intense,

00:46:18.670 --> 00:46:21.580
hard rain, killed many animals.

00:46:21.580 --> 00:46:25.320
Now, how many animals do
we kill when we have one

00:46:25.320 --> 00:46:26.700
of our rains right now?

00:46:26.700 --> 00:46:28.920
One of those really
heavy rains killed a lot

00:46:28.920 --> 00:46:31.330
of cars, I know that.

00:46:31.330 --> 00:46:34.270
Some people were
harmed, in fact, but.

00:46:34.270 --> 00:46:35.650
We had extremely hard,

00:46:35.650 --> 00:46:38.600
windy rain that knocked
down many trees.

00:46:38.600 --> 00:46:42.570
Our fodder, their food that
they collect for the winter

00:46:42.570 --> 00:46:46.100
for their animals, our fodder
was blown up into the air.

00:46:46.100 --> 00:46:48.260
We lost half of the fodder.

00:46:48.260 --> 00:46:51.630
Our ger was damaged and
knocked down in 2010.

00:46:51.630 --> 00:46:55.160
And these gers are
pretty well fixed,

00:46:55.160 --> 00:47:00.630
and yet the aadar rain can knock
them down and blow them around.

00:47:00.630 --> 00:47:04.210
Last year at the end of July
I experienced aadar boroo.

00:47:04.210 --> 00:47:06.480
That's rain, aadar rain.

00:47:06.480 --> 00:47:08.970
It was dangerously intense.

00:47:12.220 --> 00:47:17.110
And in most cases these
rains are ending up in floods

00:47:17.110 --> 00:47:20.730
when they get at Hovsgol,
near the lake itself.

00:47:20.730 --> 00:47:22.580
If you could, on the
upper left there,

00:47:22.580 --> 00:47:24.890
if you could just
walk straight out,

00:47:24.890 --> 00:47:27.120
you would actually
see the lake there.

00:47:27.120 --> 00:47:28.650
It's just beyond it.

00:47:28.650 --> 00:47:33.390
But what happens is when the
stream following an aadar rain

00:47:33.390 --> 00:47:37.750
is coming down towards the
lake, it sort of backs up.

00:47:37.750 --> 00:47:39.590
The lake is acting
as a dam for it,

00:47:39.590 --> 00:47:44.720
so it backs up in the
whole pasture area.

00:47:44.720 --> 00:47:49.650
This is a stream that originally
is about 25 feet across,

00:47:49.650 --> 00:47:50.950
nothing more than that.

00:47:50.950 --> 00:47:54.350
And you can see two
of our researchers,

00:47:54.350 --> 00:47:58.750
they're actually looking for
insects, not for fish there.

00:47:58.750 --> 00:48:04.770
So you get a perspective
on what that river is like.

00:48:04.770 --> 00:48:08.610
Now, look at above that
and over to the right,

00:48:08.610 --> 00:48:11.480
if you look just beyond --
I don't know if you can --

00:48:11.480 --> 00:48:14.670
I don't know if I can point out.

00:48:14.670 --> 00:48:17.820
If you look up in the
upper right corner there,

00:48:17.820 --> 00:48:20.440
you see dots there.

00:48:20.440 --> 00:48:24.160
There are four yaks and
a couple of horses there

00:48:24.160 --> 00:48:32.770
that got isolated out on a
little knob, not recognizing --

00:48:32.770 --> 00:48:35.320
I mean, they're sitting there
grazing and not recognizing

00:48:35.320 --> 00:48:37.760
that the whole valley
was flooding.

00:48:37.760 --> 00:48:39.640
But I leave that in for scale

00:48:39.640 --> 00:48:43.520
as you can compare the two
researchers versus the yaks

00:48:43.520 --> 00:48:47.740
and the horses for scale.

00:48:47.740 --> 00:48:52.390
So aadar rains now, all of the
herders say, and I haven't put

00:48:52.390 --> 00:48:55.050
in the analysis for that,

00:48:55.050 --> 00:48:58.720
but all of the herders are
saying the aadar rains are much

00:48:58.720 --> 00:49:00.220
more common now.

00:49:00.220 --> 00:49:01.750
We used to have these
light rains,

00:49:01.750 --> 00:49:04.320
now we're having these
very intense rains.

00:49:04.320 --> 00:49:06.840
It's not always the
only rain that occurs,

00:49:06.840 --> 00:49:10.330
but nevertheless, it is there.

00:49:10.330 --> 00:49:14.800
This is a rainfall right
here that is about two inches

00:49:14.800 --> 00:49:17.320
over a two-day period.

00:49:17.320 --> 00:49:22.140
We've had some rains more
than that, I'm afraid.

00:49:22.140 --> 00:49:27.460
So my concern, Bob's
concern for Lake Hovsgol,

00:49:27.460 --> 00:49:29.930
and I think the concern
of many people,

00:49:29.930 --> 00:49:33.450
is rather substantial
and with good reason.

00:49:33.450 --> 00:49:37.250
Our research on Lake
Hovsgol suggests

00:49:37.250 --> 00:49:40.980
that strict protection
guidelines need to be followed

00:49:40.980 --> 00:49:44.030
as the bay and shoreline
areas, the lakes,

00:49:44.030 --> 00:49:46.640
watershed are developed
for tourism

00:49:46.640 --> 00:49:49.870
and as the climate
continues to change.

00:49:49.870 --> 00:49:53.200
This is critical in order
to avoid serious problems

00:49:53.200 --> 00:49:56.970
in the future that would
very likely include blooms

00:49:56.970 --> 00:50:01.330
of nuisance aquatic plant
growths, fish kills,

00:50:01.330 --> 00:50:05.810
more flooding, and would
quickly discourage tourists

00:50:05.810 --> 00:50:09.130
from visiting the park and
all of the efforts then

00:50:09.130 --> 00:50:11.150
to build tourism would
have come to nothing.

00:50:11.150 --> 00:50:12.950
Thank you.

