00:52:48.230 --> 00:52:50.470
&gt;&gt; Robert McIntosh: The story
you tell was a story you could

00:52:50.470 --> 00:52:54.890
tell of the United
States 50, 75 years ago.

00:52:54.890 --> 00:52:56.190
&gt;&gt; Yeah.

00:52:56.190 --> 00:52:57.490
&gt;&gt; Robert McIntosh:
And the people

00:52:57.490 --> 00:53:01.560
of the United States
finally became, themselves,

00:53:01.560 --> 00:53:06.810
so upset that there
were national campaigns,

00:53:06.810 --> 00:53:12.750
just signs on TV and all those
different types of media,

00:53:12.750 --> 00:53:18.340
to tell people to care for the
landscape and don't litter.

00:53:18.340 --> 00:53:22.490
So that changed the mentality,

00:53:22.490 --> 00:53:28.310
coupled with more intense
litter patrolling, particularly

00:53:28.310 --> 00:53:32.820
in the parks, because I think if
people see litter, they litter.

00:53:32.820 --> 00:53:34.120
&gt;&gt; Right.

00:53:34.120 --> 00:53:35.420
&gt;&gt; Robert McIntosh: If
they don't see litter,

00:53:35.420 --> 00:53:37.730
they think twice about
throwing the plastic bag

00:53:37.730 --> 00:53:41.530
or the cigarettes, or
whatever, out the car window

00:53:41.530 --> 00:53:42.830
or leaving them behind.

00:53:42.830 --> 00:53:45.940
So I think it's both a role
of the government to respond

00:53:45.940 --> 00:53:49.620
to that, but most importantly
you have to change the mindset

00:53:49.620 --> 00:53:51.790
of the population,
and the best way to do

00:53:51.790 --> 00:53:55.530
that is national campaigns
to just make people aware

00:53:55.530 --> 00:53:57.510
of what they're doing
to themselves.

00:53:57.510 --> 00:54:14.440
[ Inaudible comments ]

00:54:14.440 --> 00:54:15.740
&gt;&gt; Robert McIntosh: Yeah,

00:54:15.740 --> 00:54:17.880
that's a problem not
unique to Mongolia.

00:54:17.880 --> 00:54:23.850
But again, I think even with
plastic in retail and so on,

00:54:23.850 --> 00:54:28.070
if people are educated, they
will strive to take care of it

00:54:28.070 --> 00:54:29.720
as opposed to just littering.

00:54:29.720 --> 00:54:32.940
And there are campaigns in
Europe and campaigns starting

00:54:32.940 --> 00:54:37.360
in the United States to just
try to eliminate as much plastic

00:54:37.360 --> 00:54:41.870
from the retail stream as
possible, and that's a long road

00:54:41.870 --> 00:54:45.070
to follow, but hopefully it will
be successful in those places

00:54:45.070 --> 00:54:48.920
that are trying it, and it can
be tried in Mongolia as well.

00:54:48.920 --> 00:54:50.460
&gt;&gt; Clyde Goulden: Now,
it may sound, by the way,

00:54:50.460 --> 00:54:52.730
that we're only worried
about Lake Hovsgol,

00:54:52.730 --> 00:54:54.030
but I think Bob has said enough,

00:54:54.030 --> 00:54:57.380
and I would certainly
reinforce the whole issue,

00:54:57.380 --> 00:55:00.900
that what is happening there is
happening in many of the parks.

00:55:00.900 --> 00:55:03.990
One of the things that really
attracted me to Mongolia

00:55:03.990 --> 00:55:09.270
to begin with is that they
have established a plan

00:55:09.270 --> 00:55:14.170
for protecting 15 percent,
if not more, in fact,

00:55:14.170 --> 00:55:20.640
almost 25 percent at one time,
of their area in national parks.

00:55:20.640 --> 00:55:26.560
That goal at least has reached
the 15 percent part now,

00:55:26.560 --> 00:55:31.880
and in each one of these parks,
some of them much more protected

00:55:31.880 --> 00:55:36.390
than others because they haven't
attracted people as much there,

00:55:36.390 --> 00:55:43.560
but as they do, there is an
ethic that has to be recognized

00:55:43.560 --> 00:55:48.030
and established for what
happens when you go into a park.

00:55:48.030 --> 00:55:52.890
Our National Park Service has
done a great deal and continues

00:55:52.890 --> 00:55:56.810
to do a great deal, and in
Mongolia they will, I know,

00:55:56.810 --> 00:56:00.360
catch on and begin
to do that, too.

00:56:00.360 --> 00:56:02.170
&gt;&gt; Robert McIntosh: I'll give
you a quick little case study.

00:56:02.170 --> 00:56:06.260
Three years ago we started a
Junior Ranger Program in Hatgal

00:56:06.260 --> 00:56:08.970
and this year we'll have it --
it's already started in Hankh

00:56:08.970 --> 00:56:10.640
at the northern end of the lake.

00:56:10.640 --> 00:56:14.590
After the first summer camp
a couple of the kids went

00:56:14.590 --> 00:56:18.700
to the local store in the
main strip of Hatgal and stood

00:56:18.700 --> 00:56:22.880
at the door and when people
left, they challenged them

00:56:22.880 --> 00:56:25.360
as to what they were going
to do with that plastic bag

00:56:25.360 --> 00:56:28.180
or what they were going to do
with that empty Coke bottle,

00:56:28.180 --> 00:56:30.060
and made them promise,
basically,

00:56:30.060 --> 00:56:33.650
that they would not just
throw it into the countryside.

00:56:33.650 --> 00:56:35.780
So here we've got a sixth-,

00:56:35.780 --> 00:56:40.260
seventh-grader who's already
understanding what the issues

00:56:40.260 --> 00:56:44.590
are and starting to try to
make a change, and the more

00:56:44.590 --> 00:56:47.250
that we can do that type of
thing and touch one person

00:56:47.250 --> 00:56:49.970
at a time, the problem
goes away.

00:56:52.720 --> 00:56:54.020
Yes.

00:56:54.020 --> 00:57:03.540
&gt;&gt; I agree with you about
the role of our children

00:57:03.540 --> 00:57:04.840
in all this [inaudible].

00:57:04.840 --> 00:57:13.020
It obviously worked
in the United States

00:57:37.750 --> 00:57:41.230
and we're seeing it
work in Mongolia.

00:57:41.230 --> 00:57:44.700
I want to ask about the
possible role of the people

00:57:44.700 --> 00:57:47.900
who have the guest gers
around the side of the lake

00:57:47.900 --> 00:57:53.010
and whether you see --
because we saw the same thing

00:57:53.010 --> 00:57:55.940
in a national park in
western Mongolia, the Altai,

00:57:55.940 --> 00:58:00.400
and I keep wondering whether
the role of the guides

00:58:00.400 --> 00:58:07.160
and the guests and their owners,
is it their place to report it.

00:58:07.160 --> 00:58:08.460
&gt;&gt; Robert McIntosh:
Yeah, obviously.

00:58:08.460 --> 00:58:09.760
Obviously.

00:58:09.760 --> 00:58:14.080
And they all have
different motivations

00:58:14.080 --> 00:58:16.000
and they all have
different sensitivities.

00:58:16.000 --> 00:58:19.350
Some, I think, are very strong
in terms of eliminating plastic

00:58:19.350 --> 00:58:23.880
in the waste stream and making
sure that their guests pick

00:58:23.880 --> 00:58:26.180
up trash, and if they don't,
they pick up the trash.

00:58:26.180 --> 00:58:27.480
&gt;&gt; Well, the toilets also, yeah.

00:58:27.480 --> 00:58:28.780
&gt;&gt; Robert McIntosh: And
the toilets also, yeah.

00:58:28.780 --> 00:58:30.590
I mean, we didn't get into
that topic, but that is one

00:58:30.590 --> 00:58:32.310
of the biggest topics
at the lake

00:58:32.310 --> 00:58:33.610
and in other high
tourist areas in Mongolia.

00:58:33.610 --> 00:58:34.910
The standard says
no open toilets,

00:58:34.910 --> 00:58:36.210
no outhouses, so to speak.

00:58:36.210 --> 00:58:37.510
Making that transition
is expensive and because

00:58:37.510 --> 00:58:38.810
of the climate, the
technology is very challenging.

00:58:38.810 --> 00:58:40.110
So the ADB project that Clyde
mentioned is addressing that.

00:58:40.110 --> 00:58:41.410
How successful that first phase
of that is going to be is still,

00:58:41.410 --> 00:58:42.710
I think, the jury is out.

00:58:42.710 --> 00:58:44.010
But the people around Lake
Hovsgol who live there,

00:58:44.010 --> 00:58:45.310
the ADB recognizes that.

00:58:45.310 --> 00:58:46.610
We certainly recognized
that in our study in 2013,

00:58:46.610 --> 00:58:47.910
that some of the biggest
challenges the park was going

00:58:47.910 --> 00:58:49.210
to face were transportation
issues

00:58:49.210 --> 00:58:51.510
and waste management issues.

00:58:52.750 --> 00:58:58.030
In the back.

00:58:58.030 --> 00:59:04.360
&gt;&gt; My question is besides
regulation, how [inaudible].

00:59:04.360 --> 00:59:06.140
&gt;&gt; Robert McIntosh: I
think we're starting

00:59:06.140 --> 00:59:12.690
to see that evolve.

00:59:12.690 --> 00:59:18.790
There are nuggets of groups
that tourist providers

00:59:18.790 --> 00:59:27.950
in Hatgal have created an
association to address some

00:59:27.950 --> 00:59:36.850
of these issues, so I think
slowly but surely you'll see --

00:59:36.850 --> 00:59:43.790
and in Hankh also,
slowly but surely see some

00:59:43.790 --> 00:59:50.550
of these issues being addressed
by local citizens and businesses

00:59:50.550 --> 00:59:53.960
to sustain the economic
advantage that they have,

00:59:53.960 --> 01:00:02.490
because as Clyde pointed out
in a couple of his slides,

01:00:02.490 --> 01:00:13.340
if it's a dump, people aren't
going to want to go there.

01:00:13.340 --> 01:00:15.510
Yes.

01:00:15.510 --> 01:01:34.500
[ Inaudible comments ]

01:01:34.500 --> 01:01:36.010
Have you got two or three hours?

01:01:36.010 --> 01:01:39.710
We can get into this.

01:01:39.710 --> 01:01:43.550
But in summary, I think
one of the problems

01:01:43.550 --> 01:01:47.270
in the tourist facility
development is

01:01:47.270 --> 01:01:51.380
that there are multiple layers
of approval, and depending

01:01:51.380 --> 01:01:54.220
on what way you read
this law versus that law,

01:01:54.220 --> 01:01:57.620
it's somewhat confusing as
to who has the authority.

01:01:57.620 --> 01:02:02.620
But generally speaking,
the park,

01:02:02.620 --> 01:02:04.930
the soon [phonetic]
governor, the aimag governor

01:02:04.930 --> 01:02:08.520
and the minister
approve a permit.

01:02:08.520 --> 01:02:11.840
But there's also sort
of a sideway exception

01:02:11.840 --> 01:02:15.480
that the soon governor has
permission to grant permits

01:02:15.480 --> 01:02:21.680
to local families for grazing,
and then those families set

01:02:21.680 --> 01:02:28.200
up a couple of gers for a side
principal or secondary economy.

01:02:28.200 --> 01:02:29.500
I'm not sure.

01:02:29.500 --> 01:02:33.020
But because of that, and there's
no one point of authority,

01:02:33.020 --> 01:02:37.850
people are finding ways to drive
over it, around it and under it

01:02:37.850 --> 01:02:44.290
to get -- it's going to
take a strong recognition

01:02:44.290 --> 01:02:47.640
of the problem and a new
commitment, basically,

01:02:47.640 --> 01:02:50.990
to start to try to
sort this out.

01:02:50.990 --> 01:02:53.320
There's a new director
at Lake Hovsgol.

01:02:53.320 --> 01:02:57.400
He's been there almost
two years now.

01:02:57.400 --> 01:03:01.130
He's serious about addressing
this issue, but there are a lot

01:03:01.130 --> 01:03:06.080
of factors that are forcing
him to compromise and try

01:03:06.080 --> 01:03:07.790
to make things happen
in the right way,

01:03:07.790 --> 01:03:10.920
but at least it's starting.

01:03:10.920 --> 01:03:13.200
And I can tell you in the
history of the United States,

01:03:13.200 --> 01:03:14.790
of the national parks
in the United States,

01:03:14.790 --> 01:03:17.760
a hundred years ago we had
very similar type problems.

01:03:17.760 --> 01:03:19.560
So it's not like this
can't be corrected.

01:03:19.560 --> 01:03:23.040
[ Inaudible comment ]

01:03:23.040 --> 01:03:24.340
On the which?

01:03:24.340 --> 01:03:26.040
[ Inaudible comment ]

01:03:26.040 --> 01:03:27.520
I'm sure it exists.

01:03:27.520 --> 01:03:28.820
We don't have it.

01:03:28.820 --> 01:03:34.370
But I do know that there are
more incidences in recent times

01:03:34.370 --> 01:03:36.210
than there were historically,
and you can see

01:03:36.210 --> 01:03:40.640
from the seven year or so
commercial boat operators

01:03:40.640 --> 01:03:42.800
that are taking people
out on the lakes.

01:03:42.800 --> 01:03:46.260
And I've heard stories that, you
know, life jackets are required,

01:03:46.260 --> 01:03:49.070
but they're homemade life
jackets that don't really work.

01:03:49.070 --> 01:03:52.380
And, you know, if you fall
in a lake in Virginia,

01:03:52.380 --> 01:03:54.760
the water's relatively
warm and you can survive.

01:03:54.760 --> 01:03:57.150
You fall into Lake Hovsgol,
the water temperature,

01:03:57.150 --> 01:04:00.970
even on the warmest day of
the year, is not warm enough

01:04:00.970 --> 01:04:02.270
to allow you to survive.

01:04:02.270 --> 01:04:03.900
And if you're way out in
the middle of the lake

01:04:03.900 --> 01:04:05.200
and help can't get
to you quickly,

01:04:05.200 --> 01:04:07.500
that's not going
to be a good story.

