01:04:53.140 --> 01:04:57.100
The Asian Division was
founded in 1928 and it's one

01:04:57.100 --> 01:04:59.040
of the four area
studies divisions

01:04:59.040 --> 01:05:00.960
of the Library of Congress.

01:05:00.960 --> 01:05:04.430
We are a custodial division
for Asian language materials,

01:05:04.430 --> 01:05:07.940
with over four million
volumes of monographs

01:05:07.940 --> 01:05:11.510
in over 130 Asian languages.

01:05:12.610 --> 01:05:15.040
The Mongolian collection
currently consists

01:05:15.040 --> 01:05:20.910
of about 11,000 monographs,
170 serial titles,

01:05:20.910 --> 01:05:26.310
almost 4,000 microfiche,
175 reels of microfilm,

01:05:26.310 --> 01:05:30.880
and about 600 volumes
of rare books.

01:05:30.880 --> 01:05:34.250
The first Mongolian books came
to the Library of Congress

01:05:34.250 --> 01:05:37.820
between 1893 and 1901 as gifts

01:05:37.820 --> 01:05:41.720
from the American diplomat
William Woodville Rockhill,

01:05:41.720 --> 01:05:45.640
and the rare collection
now has about 600 volumes,

01:05:45.640 --> 01:05:47.940
including complete
reprint editions

01:05:47.940 --> 01:05:50.950
of the Mongolian
Kanjur and Tanjur.

01:05:50.950 --> 01:05:53.830
This is the first Mongolian
book to come to the Library

01:05:53.830 --> 01:05:58.540
of Congress, a gift from
William Rockhill in 1893.

01:05:58.540 --> 01:06:02.200
It's a very beautiful
Mongolian edition of the Sutra

01:06:02.200 --> 01:06:05.890
of the Great Liberation,
Tharpa Chenpo in Tibetan.

01:06:05.890 --> 01:06:12.990
So in 1992 the Library began
a current acquisitions program

01:06:12.990 --> 01:06:16.810
for Mongolian through the
New Delhi field office,

01:06:16.810 --> 01:06:18.210
which continues today.

01:06:18.210 --> 01:06:21.090
We have a vendor in Ulaanbaatar

01:06:21.090 --> 01:06:25.100
who ships books via the
U.S. Embassy every month

01:06:25.100 --> 01:06:26.680
to the Library.

01:06:26.680 --> 01:06:30.560
We also acquire Mongolian
language material published

01:06:30.560 --> 01:06:34.070
worldwide, including
China, Taiwan, Russia.

01:06:34.070 --> 01:06:37.080
And we have a very small
collection of publications

01:06:37.080 --> 01:06:39.970
in Kalmyk, Buryat, and
other related languages.

01:06:47.100 --> 01:06:51.890
So I've named today's display
Sutras and Silver Lakes,

01:06:51.890 --> 01:06:56.820
Books and Scenes of Mongolia, in
honor of this conference topic.

01:07:04.040 --> 01:07:08.260
The display focuses primarily
on Hovsgol Lake and Aimag.

01:07:08.260 --> 01:07:12.770
The two glass cases include
several small sutras, sudars,

01:07:12.770 --> 01:07:16.380
about respecting nature,
surrounded by images of lakes

01:07:16.380 --> 01:07:20.190
and mountains, the landscapes
to which they belong.

01:07:20.190 --> 01:07:22.980
This part of the display will be
on view until the end of March

01:07:22.980 --> 01:07:25.280
in case you don't have
time to look at it today.

